  <h1>Training During Heat Cycles</h1>

  <div class="alert alert-info">
    <strong>Purpose:</strong> Understand female dog heat cycles, adjust training appropriately, manage public access challenges, and make informed decisions about spaying
  </div>

  <h2>Understanding Heat Cycles in Female Service Dogs</h2>

  <p>Gypsy will experience heat cycles approximately every 6-8 months until spayed. Each cycle lasts 2-4 weeks and affects her behavior, focus, and public access ability. Understanding these cycles and planning accordingly is essential for maintaining training progress and determining the right time for spaying.</p>

  <div class="alert alert-warning">
    <strong>Critical Decision:</strong> Many service dog organizations require spaying before certification. However, spaying too early (before 18-24 months) may affect bone/joint development in larger dogs. Discuss timing with your vet, considering Gypsy's role as a working dog and the physical demands of service work.
  </div>

  <article class="command-card">
    <header>
      <h3>1. The Four Phases of Heat</h3>
      <span class="difficulty-badge medium">Essential Knowledge</span>
    </header>
    <section>
      <p><strong>Goal:</strong> Recognize each phase and understand how it affects training and behavior</p>

      <details open>
        <summary><strong>Complete Heat Cycle Timeline</strong></summary>
        <table class="progression-table">
          <tr><th>Phase</th><th>Duration</th><th>Physical Signs</th><th>Behavioral Changes</th><th>Training Impact</th></tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>1. Proestrus</strong></td>
            <td>7-10 days</td>
            <td>Vulva swelling, bloody discharge, attracts males but not receptive</td>
            <td>Restlessness, clinginess, increased urination, nervous energy</td>
            <td>Moderate - focus decreases, energy changes, more distractible</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>2. Estrus</strong></td>
            <td>5-10 days</td>
            <td>Discharge turns lighter (straw-colored), vulva very swollen, receptive to males</td>
            <td>VERY distracted, may try to escape, flirty behavior, restless, anxious</td>
            <td>HIGH - major training regression, difficult to focus, poor public access</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>3. Diestrus</strong></td>
            <td>60-90 days</td>
            <td>Discharge stops, swelling decreases, hormone levels high (even if not pregnant)</td>
            <td>Returns to normal gradually, possible false pregnancy symptoms</td>
            <td>Low-Moderate - behavior normalizes over 2-3 weeks</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>4. Anestrus</strong></td>
            <td>4-5 months</td>
            <td>No signs, normal appearance</td>
            <td>Normal behavior, stable hormones</td>
            <td>None - optimal training time</td>
          </tr>
        </table>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Tracking Gypsy's Cycle</strong></summary>
        <h4>Why Track?</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Predict next cycle (plan training around it)</li>
          <li>Avoid public access during peak heat</li>
          <li>Recognize pattern (every 6 months? 8 months?)</li>
          <li>Monitor for irregularities (could indicate health issues)</li>
          <li>Plan spay surgery timing if deciding to spay</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>What to Track</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Day 1:</strong> First sign of bleeding/swelling</li>
          <li><strong>Daily Notes:</strong> Discharge color/amount, behavior changes, training performance</li>
          <li><strong>Estrus Peak:</strong> When she seems most interested in males (usually days 7-12)</li>
          <li><strong>End of Heat:</strong> When discharge stops, swelling goes down</li>
          <li><strong>Return to Normal:</strong> When behavior/focus returns to pre-heat levels</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Tracking Method</h4>
        <p>Use phone calendar, dog heat tracking app, or paper calendar. Note:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Start date of each phase</li>
          <li>Physical changes observed</li>
          <li>Behavior/training notes</li>
          <li>Public access attempts and outcomes</li>
        </ul>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Pitbull-Specific Heat Cycle Considerations</strong></summary>
        <h4>Breed Characteristics During Heat</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Strong Drive:</strong> Pitbulls often have strong breeding drive when in heat - very determined to seek males</li>
          <li><strong>Escape Artists:</strong> Normally secure fencing may not be enough - reinforce during heat</li>
          <li><strong>Male Dog Attraction:</strong> Male dogs will be VERY persistent - management is critical</li>
          <li><strong>Arousal Levels:</strong> Already high-energy breed becomes even more so</li>
          <li><strong>Focus Challenges:</strong> Normally focused pitbulls become scattered, distractible</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Safety During Heat</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Never Off-Leash:</strong> Even in "secure" areas - drive to find males overrides recall</li>
          <li><strong>Avoid Dog Parks/Group Classes:</strong> Absolutely no access to intact males</li>
          <li><strong>Supervised Bathroom Breaks:</strong> Stay with her, don't let her wander yard</li>
          <li><strong>Secure Home:</strong> Intact male dogs can smell female in heat from miles away - may come to your property</li>
        </ul>
      </details>
    </section>
  </article>

  <article class="command-card">
    <header>
      <h3>2. Training Modifications During Heat</h3>
      <span class="difficulty-badge high">Practical Adjustments</span>
    </header>
    <section>
      <p><strong>Goal:</strong> Maintain training progress while accommodating hormonal changes</p>

      <details open>
        <summary><strong>Training Plan by Heat Phase</strong></summary>
        <h4>Proestrus (Days 1-10): Moderate Adjustments</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Reduce Session Length:</strong> 5-7 minutes instead of 10-15</li>
          <li><strong>Lower Expectations:</strong> Accept 70% success rate instead of 80%</li>
          <li><strong>Higher Value Rewards:</strong> Use best treats to maintain motivation</li>
          <li><strong>Familiar Environments:</strong> Train at home or very familiar locations only</li>
          <li><strong>Maintenance Mode:</strong> Practice known behaviors, don't introduce new tasks</li>
          <li><strong>Public Access:</strong> Low-traffic, essential trips only if necessary</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Estrus (Days 10-20): Maximum Modification</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Take Training Break:</strong> Focus on maintenance only (basic commands casually throughout day)</li>
          <li><strong>No Formal Sessions:</strong> She likely can't focus enough for productive training</li>
          <li><strong>Home Practice Only:</strong> Quick sits/downs for meals, calm behaviors</li>
          <li><strong>NO Public Access:</strong> Too distractible, unfair to her and disruptive to public</li>
          <li><strong>Mental Enrichment Instead:</strong> Puzzle feeders, sniff games, low-key activities</li>
          <li><strong>Exercise Carefully:</strong> Walks for potty only, avoid areas with male dogs</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Early Diestrus (Days 20-30): Gradual Return</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Resume Light Training:</strong> Start with 5-minute sessions, known commands</li>
          <li><strong>Rebuild Gradually:</strong> Don't expect pre-heat performance immediately</li>
          <li><strong>Test Focus:</strong> If she's attentive, slowly increase difficulty</li>
          <li><strong>Postpone Public Access:</strong> Wait until you see 3-5 days of good focus</li>
          <li><strong>Be Patient:</strong> May take 1-2 weeks to return to normal</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Late Diestrus & Anestrus: Normal Training</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Full Training Resumes:</strong> Back to normal schedule and expectations</li>
          <li><strong>Make Up Lost Ground:</strong> This is optimal training time - 4-5 months until next heat</li>
          <li><strong>Public Access Focus:</strong> Maximize public exposure during this stable period</li>
          <li><strong>New Task Introduction:</strong> Introduce challenging new tasks when hormones are stable</li>
        </ul>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Preventing Regression</strong></summary>
        <h4>The Regression Problem</h4>
        <p>Many handlers report that behaviors regress during heat and take weeks to recover. This is normal but can be minimized.</p>

        <h4>Strategies</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Don't Stop Completely:</strong> Even 2-3 minutes per day maintains neural pathways</li>
          <li><strong>Casual Practice:</strong> Ask for sits before meals, downs while watching TV - life rewards</li>
          <li><strong>High-Value Reinforcement:</strong> When you do train, make it VERY rewarding</li>
          <li><strong>Focus on Easiest Tasks:</strong> Practice her strongest, most reliable behaviors</li>
          <li><strong>Avoid Frustration:</strong> Yours and hers - if it's not working, take a break</li>
          <li><strong>Document Pattern:</strong> After 2-3 cycles, you'll know her specific regression pattern</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Realistic Expectations</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>First heat after starting training: Expect 2-4 week setback</li>
          <li>Success rate may drop 20-30% during heat</li>
          <li>Full recovery: 2-3 weeks after heat ends</li>
          <li>Each subsequent heat: You'll manage better as you learn her pattern</li>
        </ul>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Behavioral Changes to Expect</strong></summary>
        <table class="progression-table">
          <tr><th>Behavior</th><th>What You'll See</th><th>Management</th></tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Decreased Focus</td>
            <td>Difficulty maintaining attention, easily distracted, slower response</td>
            <td>Shorter sessions, higher rewards, lower expectations</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Increased Anxiety</td>
            <td>Clingy, whining, restlessness, pacing</td>
            <td>Extra comfort, calm environments, avoid stressful situations</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Frequent Urination</td>
            <td>Needs to go out more often, marking behavior</td>
            <td>More frequent potty breaks, be patient</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Mood Swings</td>
            <td>Irritable, then affectionate, unpredictable</td>
            <td>Give space when needed, don't force interaction</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Appetite Changes</td>
            <td>May eat less or more than usual</td>
            <td>Adjust portions if needed, maintain schedule</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Nesting (if false pregnancy)</td>
            <td>Gathering toys, protective of items, restless</td>
            <td>Provide comfort, vet check if severe</td>
          </tr>
        </table>
      </details>
