  <article class="command-card">
    <header>
      <h3>3. Public Access During Heat</h3>
      <span class="difficulty-badge high">Critical Decision-Making</span>
    </header>
    <section>
      <p><strong>Goal:</strong> Make informed decisions about public access during heat cycles</p>

      <details open>
        <summary><strong>The Public Access Question</strong></summary>
        <h4>Legal Rights</h4>
        <p>Under ADA, you CAN take a service dog in heat into public spaces IF:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>She is under control</li>
          <li>She is housebroken (no accidents in public)</li>
          <li>She can perform her tasks reliably</li>
          <li>She is not disruptive</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Practical Reality</h4>
        <p>Most service dog handlers do NOT take dogs in heat into public because:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Focus Issues:</strong> Dog often can't perform tasks reliably</li>
          <li><strong>Male Dog Reactions:</strong> Intact males become very interested, creating safety/disruption issues</li>
          <li><strong>Hygiene Concerns:</strong> Risk of discharge on floors/furniture even with protective garments</li>
          <li><strong>Fairness to Dog:</strong> High stress for her to work when hormones are driving distraction</li>
          <li><strong>Public Perception:</strong> Adds to stigma if dog is unfocused or disruptive</li>
        </ul>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Hygiene Management</strong></summary>
        <h4>If You Must Work During Heat</h4>
        <p><strong>Protective Garments:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Dog Diapers:</strong> Washable or disposable, with tail hole</li>
          <li><strong>Fitted Correctly:</strong> Must be snug enough not to leak but comfortable</li>
          <li><strong>Change Frequently:</strong> Every 2-3 hours minimum</li>
          <li><strong>Hygiene Wipes:</strong> Clean her vulva area regularly</li>
          <li><strong>Bring Extras:</strong> Spare diapers, wipes, disposal bags</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Home Management</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Washable Bedding:</strong> Easy to clean when discharge happens</li>
          <li><strong>Avoid Fabric Furniture:</strong> Keep her off during peak discharge days or use protective covers</li>
          <li><strong>Tile/Hardwood Preferred:</strong> Easier to clean than carpet</li>
          <li><strong>Regular Cleaning:</strong> Clean vulva area 2-3x daily</li>
        </ul>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Alternative Support During Heat</strong></summary>
        <p>If Gypsy can't perform service dog tasks during heat, plan for 2-3 weeks without her help:</p>

        <h4>Backup Plans</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Minimize Public Outings:</strong> Shop online, use delivery services for groceries</li>
          <li><strong>Telehealth Appointments:</strong> If possible, avoid in-person appointments during this time</li>
          <li><strong>Buddy System:</strong> Have friend/family accompany you if you must go out</li>
          <li><strong>Medication Adjustment:</strong> Talk to doctor about temporary increase in PTSD meds during this period</li>
          <li><strong>Home-Based Coping:</strong> Extra therapy sessions via telehealth, increased use of coping skills</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Self-Care During This Time</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Acknowledge this is hard - it's okay to struggle without her support</li>
          <li>Lower expectations for yourself (fewer outings, smaller goals)</li>
          <li>Use other coping mechanisms more intensively</li>
          <li>Remember it's temporary (2-3 weeks)</li>
          <li>Plan something positive for when heat ends (public outing as "celebration")</li>
        </ul>
      </details>
    </section>
  </article>

  <article class="command-card">
    <header>
      <h3>4. Spaying Decision for Service Dogs</h3>
      <span class="difficulty-badge high">Critical Long-Term Decision</span>
    </header>
    <section>
      <p><strong>Goal:</strong> Make informed decision about if and when to spay</p>

      <details open>
        <summary><strong>Arguments FOR Spaying</strong></summary>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Eliminates Heat Cycles:</strong> No more 2-3 week training disruptions every 6-8 months</li>
          <li><strong>Health Benefits:</strong> Prevents pyometra (life-threatening uterine infection), eliminates risk of ovarian/uterine cancer, reduces mammary cancer risk</li>
          <li><strong>Behavior Stability:</strong> More consistent temperament and focus year-round</li>
          <li><strong>Public Access:</strong> No hygiene concerns or male dog attractions</li>
          <li><strong>Certification Requirements:</strong> Many organizations require it</li>
          <li><strong>Easier Management:</strong> No need to track cycles, restrict activities, prevent pregnancy</li>
          <li><strong>Longevity:</strong> Spayed dogs often live longer due to reduced disease risk</li>
        </ul>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Arguments FOR Waiting or Not Spaying</strong></summary>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Growth Plate Closure:</strong> Hormones regulate bone growth - spaying before 18-24 months may affect joint development</li>
          <li><strong>Working Dog Considerations:</strong> Some research suggests waiting until physical maturity for athletic/working dogs</li>
          <li><strong>CCL Injury Risk:</strong> Some studies show increased cruciate ligament injury risk in spayed large breed dogs</li>
          <li><strong>Coat Changes:</strong> Some dogs' coats change texture after spaying</li>
          <li><strong>Weight Management:</strong> Spayed dogs have lower metabolism - easier weight gain</li>
          <li><strong>Surgical Risks:</strong> Any surgery carries risks (though spay is routine)</li>
        </ul>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Timing Recommendations</strong></summary>
        <h4>Veterinary Consensus for Working Dogs</h4>
        <p><strong>Ideal Timing: 18-24 months (after physical maturity but before repeated heat cycles)</strong></p>

        <h4>Rationale</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Growth plates typically close by 18 months in medium/large breeds</li>
          <li>Full physical maturity reached</li>
          <li>Minimizes joint/bone development concerns</li>
          <li>Still young enough to have health benefits</li>
          <li>Avoids multiple heat cycles disrupting critical training period</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Special Consideration for Gypsy (18 months old now)</h4>
        <p><strong>Options:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Spay Soon (18-20 months):</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Pros: Done with heat disruptions, focus on training, likely past growth concerns</li>
              <li>Cons: Very minor risk of joint development impact</li>
              <li>Best if: She's had 1-2 heat cycles already, you're struggling with heat disruptions</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Wait Until 24 Months:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Pros: Absolutely no bone/joint growth concerns, fully physically mature</li>
              <li>Cons: 1-2 more heat cycles to manage</li>
              <li>Best if: You're managing heats okay, want absolute certainty of physical maturity</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ol>

        <h4>Consult Your Vet</h4>
        <p>Factors they'll consider:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Gypsy's growth status (is she still growing?)</li>
          <li>Joint health assessment</li>
          <li>Overall health and surgical risk</li>
          <li>Your training timeline and needs</li>
          <li>Heat cycle history (how many so far? How disruptive?)</li>
        </ul>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary><strong>Spay Surgery and Recovery</strong></summary>
        <h4>Timeline</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Spay During Anestrus:</strong> NOT during heat or shortly after (wait 2-3 months after heat ends)</li>
          <li><strong>Recovery Time:</strong> 10-14 days restricted activity, 4 weeks no intense work</li>
          <li><strong>Return to Training:</strong> Light training after 2 weeks, full training after 4-6 weeks</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Planning Around Spay</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Schedule During Anestrus:</strong> When hormones are stable (not right after heat)</li>
          <li><strong>Plan Training Break:</strong> Expect 4-6 weeks of modified training</li>
          <li><strong>Avoid Major Events:</strong> Don't schedule certification tests within 8 weeks post-spay</li>
          <li><strong>Arrange Help:</strong> You'll need to prevent jumping, running, rough play during recovery</li>
          <li><strong>Mental Enrichment:</strong> Plan low-impact mental stimulation during recovery (puzzle feeders, scent work, gentle training)</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Post-Spay Expectations</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Behavior:</strong> May take 1-3 months for hormones to fully clear, behavior to stabilize</li>
          <li><strong>Weight:</strong> Monitor closely, may need reduced calories (10-20% less)</li>
          <li><strong>Energy:</strong> Should return to normal after recovery</li>
          <li><strong>Coat:</strong> May change slightly in texture (usually minimal in pitbulls)</li>
          <li><strong>Training:</strong> Most dogs perform better post-spay due to stable hormones</li>
        </ul>
      </details>
    </section>
  </article>

  <div class="alert alert-success">
    <strong>Summary:</strong> Heat cycles are a normal but challenging part of training intact female service dogs. Expect training disruptions every 6-8 months, plan for 2-3 weeks of modified work, and avoid public access during peak heat. Most handlers choose to spay between 18-24 months to eliminate these disruptions while ensuring physical maturity. Work with your vet to determine the best timing for Gypsy based on her individual development and your training needs.
